# Kubernetes Installation & First Deployment Notes

# Prerequisites

To work with Kubernetes locally, you need two things:

1. **kubectl** – the command-line tool used to communicate with the Kubernetes API server.
2. **Minikube** – creates a local Kubernetes cluster for learning and testing.

---

# Step 1: Install kubectl

`kubectl` is the CLI (Command Line Interface) used to send commands to a Kubernetes cluster.

Flow:

```text
User
   │
kubectl
   │
Kubernetes API Server
   │
Kubernetes Cluster
```

Install using Snap:

```bash
sudo snap install kubectl --classic
```

> **Note:** Running:
>
> ```bash
> sudo apt install kubectl
> ```
>
> often fails on Ubuntu because the Kubernetes APT repository is not configured by default. Using Snap or adding the official Kubernetes repository are the common installation methods.

Verify the installation:

```bash
kubectl version --client
```

---

# Step 2: Install Minikube

Minikube creates a **single-node Kubernetes cluster** on your local machine.

Download and install:

```bash
curl -LO https://github.com/kubernetes/minikube/releases/latest/download/minikube-linux-amd64

sudo install minikube-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/minikube && rm minikube-linux-amd64
```

Verify the installation:

```bash
minikube version
```

---

# Step 3: Start the Kubernetes Cluster

Since Docker is installed on the system, Minikube can use Docker as its driver.

Start the cluster:

```bash
minikube start --driver=docker
```

This command:

* Creates a local Kubernetes cluster.
* Starts the control plane.
* Creates a worker node (single-node cluster).
* Configures `kubectl` to communicate with the cluster automatically.

---

# Step 4: Verify the Cluster

Check whether the node is running:

```bash
kubectl get nodes
```

Example output:

```text
NAME        STATUS   ROLES           AGE   VERSION
minikube    Ready    control-plane   2m    v1.xx.x
```

If the node status is **Ready**, the cluster is running correctly.

